title: Protests and marches: letting the police know

heading_context: Protests and marches: letting the police know
chunks.html_content: By law you must tell the police in writing 6 days before a public march if you’re the organiser.
chunks.plain_content:
Protests and marches: letting the police know
By law you must tell the police in writing 6 days before a public march if you’re the organiser.

heading_context: Protests and marches: letting the police know
chunks.html_content:
Tell the police the:

  • date and time of the march
  • route
  • the names and addresses of the organisers

The police have the power to:

  • limit or change the route of your march
  • set any other condition of your march

heading_context: Protests and marches: letting the police know
chunks.html_content: If you arrange a march at short notice, you must still tell the police as soon as you can.
chunks.plain_content:
Protests and marches: letting the police know
If you arrange a march at short notice, you must still tell the police as soon as you can.

heading_context: Protests and marches: letting the police know
chunks.html_content:
The police can also:

  • change the location
  • limit how long a rally lasts
  • limit the amount of people who attend
  • stop a sit-down protest if it blocks road traffic or public walkways

If there’s no march organised as part of your protest, you do not have to tell the police.
